[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there a way to define left/right inverses in an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-category? The <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>-categorical counterpart would be a morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> for which there exists a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">fg=1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> (or dually).</p>",
        "id": 238342587,
        "sender_full_name": "Francesco Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1620752309
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, it's a 2-simplex whose long edge is degenerate and one of whose other edges is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 238353399,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1620755009
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276480\">Reid Barton</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Partial.20inverses.20in.20.24.5Cinfty.24-categories/near/238353399\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yes, it's a 2-simplex whose long edge is degenerate and one of whose other edges is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>don't I need some higher data maybe?</p>",
        "id": 238359578,
        "sender_full_name": "Francesco Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1620757501
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Remember, the simplicial set that looks like a 2-simplex contains degenerate simplexes of all higher dimensions.  I think these provide all the higher data.</p>",
        "id": 238360398,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620757813
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(When I say \"the simplicial set that looks like a 2-simplex\", I really mean the \"simplicial 2-simplex\".   There's a simplicial set called the <strong>simplicial n-simplex</strong>, which is really the representable of the object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[n] \\in \\Delta</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span></span></span></span>.   It contains a lot of higher-dimensional simplexes, but they're all degenerate.)</p>",
        "id": 238360711,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620757930
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So you mean that I can understand partial inverses actually just as partial inverses in the homotopy category?</p>",
        "id": 238369559,
        "sender_full_name": "Francesco Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1620761711
    }
]